{
  "question": "Why does my thermostat keep cycling the heat on and off every few minutes, and how can I fix it?",
  "answer": "Plan: Diagnose common thermostat and HVAC short-cycling causes by checking thermostat settings, confirming power/heat demand, and verifying proper sensor operation, then adjust or replace components as needed. Safety info: Turn off power at the furnace/air handler switch before removing the thermostat faceplate or handling any wiring; verify proper voltage after reconnecting. Tools required: 1) screwdriver, 2) multimeter, 3) flashlight. Steps:\n1. Check the thermostat settings: confirm the mode is set to Heat, verify the setpoint is at least 2\u20135\u00b0F above the current room temperature, and make sure any energy-saving schedules or minimum run/off timers are not causing frequent cycling.\n2. Inspect thermostat connections and contacts: turn off power, open the thermostat cover, and verify the R (power), W (heat call), and C/R-wire terminations are tight and corrosion-free, then reassemble.\n3. Verify HVAC wiring and furnace operation triggers: check the HVAC cabinet where W-call runs to confirm the circuit activates the inducer/ignition as expected, and use a multimeter to confirm stable voltage during calls.\n4. Test and clean/replace the thermostat batteries (if present) and check the sensor calibration/thermistor cleanliness, then set a realistic heat differential and observe if cycling normalizes over multiple calls.\n5. If cycling persists, check the furnace/heat pump control board for fault codes or timing limits and consider a thermostat replacement that supports your equipment to prevent short-cycle behavior.\nTip: Tighten thermostat terminals firmly and turn off power at the system switch before removing or moving thermostat wiring.",
  "equipment_problem": "Thermostat short-cycles the heating system, turning the heat on and off every few minutes",
